Perplexity Search Ads
---------------------

Speaking of the search upstart, from Digiday ( https://digiday.com/media-bu=
ying/perplexitys-pitch-deck-offers-advertisers-a-new-vision-for-ai-search/ =
) :

Perplexity=E2=80=99s plans for competing in the ad space are becoming a bit=
 less puzzling. A new advertiser pitch deck shows how the AI search startup=
 hopes to win over advertiser later this year as it works to set itself apa=
rt from competing startups like ChatGPT and giants like Google.

According to a copy of the pitch deck obtained by Digiday, the plan is to i=
ntegrate ads within users=E2=80=99 queries and answers =E2=80=94 potentiall=
y as soon as the fourth quarter of 2024. One page in the deck says buying a=
ds with Perplexity can help brands =E2=80=9Creach, educate and spark curios=
ity of potential customers at high-leverage moments.=E2=80=9D The company i=
s also pitching an educated, affluent and engaged user base. Although the p=
itch deck didn=E2=80=99t talk about pricing, a source within Perplexity con=
firmed the goal is to target CPMs =E2=80=9Cnorth of $50.=E2=80=9D Total mon=
thly U.S. queries now totaling 230 million =E2=80=94 eight times the total =
queries it had just a year ago, according to the deck.

One example in the pitch deck shows a Nike ad sponsoring a related question=
 when a user asked about basketball shoes or options for sponsored videos a=
longside a desktop version. Another shows a sponsored Marriott Bonvoy video=
 ad next to someone asking about =E2=80=9Cbest European travel destinations=
 for families.=E2=80=9D Another option is to have =E2=80=9Cbranded explanat=
ory text=E2=80=9D that appears above sponsored and organic related question=
s.

More than a dozen advertising categories are listed as key for the initial =
launch, according to the pitch deck. Some of those include technology, heal=
th and pharma, arts and entertainment and finance food and beverage, sports=
, science and travel. Others are business, industrial and B2B; internet and=
 telecom; games; automotive; home and garden; beauty and fitness; retail; a=
nd shopping.

The key word in this excerpt isn=E2=80=99t a word at all: it=E2=80=99s an a=
cronym. =E2=80=9CCPM=E2=80=9D means =E2=80=9Ccost per mille=E2=80=9D, which=
 is the amount an advertiser pays for a thousand impressions; it=E2=80=99s =
the unit of measurement for your bog-standard display advertising. Perplexi=
ty isn=E2=80=99t the only company to use this type of measurement for adver=
tising; consider this press release:

Google Inc., developer of the award-winning Google search engine, announced=
 today at the Jupiter Online Advertising Forum that its targeted online adv=
ertising program is delivering highly effective results for advertisers wit=
h click-through rates four times higher than the industry average for tradi=
tional banner advertising. Google=E2=80=99s advertising program was launche=
d earlier this year with a distinctive approach that helps advertisers targ=
et and refine their campaigns to ensure optimal campaign performance.

Google=E2=80=99s advertising program enables advertisers to purchase keywor=
ds, keyword phrases or categories to target potential customers. Google use=
s its proprietary ad serving system to carefully match a user=E2=80=99s sea=
rch query with a closely related advertisement based on keywords and catego=
ries. For example, entering the query =E2=80=9Chealth insurance=E2=80=9D in=
to the search box on Google=E2=80=99s home page produces search results and=
 a text-based advertisement that relate to purchasing health insurance onli=
ne. This enhances the overall search experience for Google users by providi=
ng relevant, useful information on the search results page, and benefits ad=
vertisers by increasing the likelihood that users will click on a specifica=
lly targeted ad.

That press release is, needless to say, pretty old: it was published on Aug=
ust 16, 2000 ( https://googlepress.blogspot.com/2000/08/googles-targeted-ke=
yword-ad-program.html ). It was also obsolete before it even launched; two =
years earlier GoTo, a competing search engine, had launched the concept of =
cost-per-click, where advertisers only paid if a consumer actually clicked =
on their ad. The price for that click was set by an auction. Two years late=
r and Google adopted cost-per-click advertising (and got sued by GoTo, then=
 renamed Overture), and the company was off to the revenue races.

So surely that is next for Perplexity, if not now, then a couple of years d=
own the road?

