ive.

* As long as Google was providing ten blue links, it could serve everyone, =
no matter their values; after all, the user decided which link to click.
* By providing ads alongside those ten blue links, Google deputized the end=
 user to choose the winner of the auction it conducted amongst advertisers;=
 those advertisers would pay a premium to win that auction because their po=
tential customer was affirmatively choosing to go to their site, which both=
 meant a higher chance of conversion and the possibility of building a long=
-term relationship that increased lifetime value.

AI threatens both:

* Because AI reduces supply to one answer, which, if the subject rests on s=
ubjective values, can never satisfy everyone, Google risks upsetting a sign=
ificant portion of demand, weakening its Aggregator position and potentiall=
y decreasing its leverage on costs.
* Because AI gives an answer instead of links, there is no organic place to=
 put the auction decision; yes, Google could have affiliate links or put so=
me ads alongside the AI answer, but both options are likely less attractive=
 to advertisers and may command less of a premium.

A CPM-based display advertising model is, to be clear, the easiest possible=
 advertising product to start out with: you sell the ads with a sales team =
and choose the right ad deterministically based on keywords. To that end, =
=E2=80=9Ceasy=E2=80=9D is the most obvious explanation for why Perplexity i=
s reportedly launching the product in this report. It is very much unclear,=
 though, whether Perplexity or any AI search engine will follow the path Go=
ogle walked so long ago, or, perhaps more accurately, if it will ever monet=
ize as well as cost-per-click search ads do today.

Google is, unsurprisingly, avoiding AI-generated answers for high value com=
mercial searches; for example, I did a search for =E2=80=9Cbest life insura=
nce for expats=E2=80=9D:

Perplexity gave what seems, at first glance, to be a more useful answer, wi=
th links to guides for choosing the best plan:

Some of those links =E2=80=94 and some of the text =E2=80=94 is very valuab=
le, with direct recommendations and links to plans; surely Perplexity could=
 sell that space? The pitch deck Digiday saw says no:

In April, Chief Business Officer Dmitry Shevelenko told Digiday about the p=
lans for a road map focused on =E2=80=9Caccuracy, speed and readability.=E2=
=80=9D Shevelenko also noted the company couldn=E2=80=99t use the same mode=
l as Google and couldn=E2=80=99t pay companies like Apple $10 billion a yea=
